  "articleSummary": "The article argues that multiple-choice questions (MCQs) are a powerful, underappreciated tool for deep learning when designed intentionally, particularly in technical education. It emphasizes that effective distractors—wrong answers crafted to reflect real-world misconceptions, syntax overlaps, or cross-platform confusion—act as a \"curriculum\" by exposing learners' mental models and forcing instructional clarity. Using PostgreSQL as an example, the author demonstrates how a single MCQ can address multiple expertise levels and dialect-specific knowledge, framing the quiz-building process as a feedback loop that sharpens both teaching and content creation. The tone is analytical and reflective, blending personal experience with pedagogical insight. The intended audience includes educators and technical writers seeking to improve learning outcomes through deliberate quiz design.",
